{
  "id": "fundamental-theorem",
  "title": "The Fundamental Theorem of Calculus",
  "order": 9,
  "estimatedMinutes": 8,
  "conceptTags": ["ftc", "antiderivative"],
  "published": true,
  "steps": [
    {
      "id": "ftc-step-1",
      "type": "read",
      "conceptTag": "ftc",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "body": "You've met both big ideas of calculus: the derivative (a slope, a rate of change) and the integral (an accumulated area). The Fundamental Theorem of Calculus says these two are inverse operations — each one undoes the other."
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "body": "To see it, think of the area you sweep out as its own function. Call A(x) the area under f from a fixed start up to x:"
        },
        {
          "type": "math",
          "latex": "A(x) = \\int_0^x f(t)\\,dt",
          "display": true
        }
      ],
      "feedback": { "correct": "", "incorrect": "", "hint": "" }
    },
    {
      "id": "ftc-step-2",
      "type": "slider_graph",
      "conceptTag": "ftc",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "body": "Take f(x) = 2. Drag x and watch the area A(x) grow. Each time x increases by 1, by how much does the shaded area increase?"
        },
        {
          "type": "math",
          "latex": "f(x) = 2"
        }
      ],
      "interaction": {
        "graph": {
          "fn": "2",
          "domain": [0, 5],
          "yDomain": [0, 4],
          "sliderLabel": "x",
          "xLabel": "x",
          "yLabel": "f",
          "showSecant": false,
          "showValue": false,
          "showArea": true,
          "areaStart": 0,
          "showAreaValue": false,
          "areaReadoutMath": true,
          "integrand": "2",
          "sliderMin": 0,
          "sliderMax": 5,
          "sliderStep": 1,
          "initialSlider": 0
        },
        "hintAfterAttempts": 1,
        "answer": { "type": "numeric", "value": 2, "tolerance": 0.1 }
      },
      "feedback": {
        "correct": "Exactly — the area grows by 2 per step, which is precisely the height f(x) = 2. The rate the area grows equals the function's value.",
        "incorrect": "Each step adds a strip of height f(x) = 2 and width 1. How much area is that?",
        "hint": "Each new strip has area 2 × 1 = 2, so the area grows by 2 per step — the same as the height."
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "ftc-step-3",
      "type": "read",
      "conceptTag": "ftc",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "body": "That's the heart of it. The rate at which the area A(x) grows is exactly the height of the curve at that point. In derivative language, the derivative of the area function is f itself:"
        },
        {
          "type": "math",
          "latex": "\\frac{d}{dx}\\int_0^x f(t)\\,dt = f(x)",
          "display": true
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "body": "Differentiating an integral hands you back the original function. Integrating and differentiating cancel out."
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "body": "Watch it happen: drag x along f(x) = x. The readouts show the height f(x) and the area A(x) so far. Where the curve is taller, the shaded area piles up faster — the area's growth rate is just the height."
        }
      ],
      "interaction": {
        "graph": {
          "fn": "x",
          "domain": [0, 5],
          "yDomain": [0, 5],
          "sliderLabel": "x",
          "xLabel": "x",
          "yLabel": "f",
          "showSecant": false,
          "showValue": true,
          "showArea": true,
          "areaStart": 0,
          "showAreaValue": true,
          "areaReadoutMath": true,
          "integrand": "x",
          "sliderMin": 0,
          "sliderMax": 5,
          "sliderStep": 0.1,
          "initialSlider": 0
        }
      },
      "feedback": { "correct": "", "incorrect": "", "hint": "" }
    },
    {
      "id": "ftc-step-4",
      "type": "slider_graph",
      "conceptTag": "ftc",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "body": "Now f(x) = x, where the height changes. Drag x to 4. By the theorem, the rate the area is growing at x = 4 equals f(4). What is f(4)?"
        },
        {
          "type": "math",
          "latex": "f(x) = x"
        }
      ],
      "interaction": {
        "graph": {
          "fn": "x",
          "domain": [0, 5],
          "yDomain": [0, 5],
          "sliderLabel": "x",
          "xLabel": "x",
          "yLabel": "f",
          "showSecant": false,
          "showValue": false,
          "showArea": true,
          "areaStart": 0,
          "showAreaValue": false,
          "areaReadoutMath": true,
          "integrand": "x",
          "sliderMin": 0,
          "sliderMax": 5,
          "sliderStep": 1,
          "initialSlider": 0
        },
        "hintAfterAttempts": 1,
        "answer": { "type": "numeric", "value": 4, "tolerance": 0.1 }
      },
      "feedback": {
        "correct": "Right — f(4) = 4, so at x = 4 the area is growing at a rate of 4 units of area per unit of x. The taller the curve, the faster the area accumulates.",
        "incorrect": "The growth rate equals the height f(x) = x. Evaluate that height at x = 4.",
        "hint": "f(x) = x means f(4) = 4 — and that's how fast the area is growing there."
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "ftc-step-5",
      "type": "read",
      "conceptTag": "antiderivative",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "body": "This inverse relationship gives a powerful shortcut for computing areas. To find a definite integral, find an antiderivative F — a function whose derivative is f — then subtract its values at the endpoints:"
        },
        {
          "type": "math",
          "latex": "\\int_a^b f(x)\\,dx = F(b) - F(a), \\quad \\text{where } F'(x) = f(x)",
          "display": true
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "body": "No infinite strips required — just an antiderivative and a subtraction."
        }
      ],
      "feedback": { "correct": "", "incorrect": "", "hint": "" }
    },
    {
      "id": "ftc-step-6",
      "type": "numeric",
      "conceptTag": "antiderivative",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "body": "Compute the integral below. An antiderivative of 2x is x² (since the derivative of x² is 2x). Evaluate F(3) − F(0)."
        },
        {
          "type": "math",
          "latex": "\\int_0^3 2x\\,dx = \\left[x^2\\right]_0^3"
        }
      ],
      "interaction": {
        "graph": {
          "fn": "2*x",
          "domain": [0, 4],
          "yDomain": [0, 8],
          "xLabel": "x",
          "yLabel": "f",
          "showArea": true,
          "areaStart": 0,
          "initialSlider": 3,
          "static": true
        },
        "answer": { "type": "numeric", "value": 9, "tolerance": 0.1 }
      },
      "feedback": {
        "correct": "Exactly — F(3) − F(0) = 3² − 0² = 9.",
        "incorrect": "Use the antiderivative F(x) = x²: evaluate F(3) − F(0).",
        "hint": "3² − 0² = 9 − 0 = 9."
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "ftc-step-6b",
      "type": "slider_graph",
      "conceptTag": "antiderivative",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "body": "A definite integral can start anywhere. Find the value of $t$ for which this integral equals 8, then drag the slider there."
        },
        {
          "type": "math",
          "latex": "\\int_1^t 2x\\,dx = 8",
          "display": true
        }
      ],
      "interaction": {
        "graph": {
          "fn": "2*x",
          "domain": [0, 4],
          "yDomain": [0, 8],
          "sliderLabel": "t",
          "xLabel": "x",
          "yLabel": "f",
          "showSecant": false,
          "showValue": false,
          "showArea": true,
          "areaStart": 1,
          "showAreaValue": false,
          "areaReadoutMath": true,
          "integrand": "2x",
          "sliderMin": 1,
          "sliderMax": 3.5,
          "sliderStep": 0.1,
          "initialSlider": 1
        },
        "hintAfterAttempts": 1,
        "answer": { "type": "slider", "value": 3, "tolerance": 0.15 }
      },
      "feedback": {
        "correct": "Yes — $t^2 - 1 = 8$ gives $t^2 = 9$, so $t = 3$. The lower limit is 1, not 0, and the Fundamental Theorem handles it just the same.",
        "incorrect": "Set $t^2 - 1 = 8$ and solve for $t$, then drag the slider there.",
        "hint": "$t^2 - 1 = 8 \\to t^2 = 9 \\to t = 3$."
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "ftc-step-7",
      "type": "multiple_choice",
      "conceptTag": "antiderivative",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "body": "Which function is an antiderivative of $f(x) = x^2$? (Its derivative should be $x^2$.)"
        }
      ],
      "interaction": {
        "graph": {
          "fn": "x^2",
          "domain": [0, 3],
          "yDomain": [0, 9],
          "xLabel": "x",
          "yLabel": "f",
          "showArea": true,
          "areaStart": 0,
          "initialSlider": 2,
          "static": true
        },
        "answer": {
          "type": "multiple_choice",
          "options": [
            "$\\frac{x^3}{3}$",
            "$2x$",
            "$3x^2$",
            "$x^3$"
          ],
          "correctIndex": 0
        }
      },
      "feedback": {
        "correct": "Correct — the derivative of $\\frac{x^3}{3}$ is $x^2$, so $\\frac{x^3}{3}$ is an antiderivative. That's exactly why the area under $x^2$ is $\\frac{b^3}{3}$.",
        "incorrect": "Differentiate each option and see which gives $x^2$ back.",
        "hint": "$\\frac{d}{dx}\\left(\\frac{x^3}{3}\\right) = \\frac{3x^2}{3} = x^2$. That's the one."
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "ftc-step-8",
      "type": "read",
      "conceptTag": "ftc",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "body": "That's the whole arc of introductory calculus: derivatives measure how things change, integrals accumulate them into areas, and the Fundamental Theorem shows the two are inverses — letting you compute areas with antiderivatives."
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "body": "Slopes and areas, finally tied together. Next, you'll put it all to work — integrating whole polynomials with the reverse power rule."
        }
      ],
      "feedback": { "correct": "", "incorrect": "", "hint": "" }
    }
  ],
  "practiceBank": [
    {
      "id": "ftc-practice-1",
      "type": "match",
      "conceptTag": "antiderivative",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "body": "Match each function to its antiderivative — the function whose derivative gives it back."
        }
      ],
      "interaction": {
        "answer": {
          "type": "match",
          "pairs": [
            {
              "prompt": "$x^2$",
              "match": "$\\frac{x^3}{3}$"
            },
            {
              "prompt": "$x$",
              "match": "$\\frac{x^2}{2}$"
            },
            {
              "prompt": "$x^3$",
              "match": "$\\frac{x^4}{4}$"
            },
            {
              "prompt": "$1$",
              "match": "$x$"
            }
          ],
          "distractors": [
            "$\\frac{x^3}{2}$"
          ]
        }
      },
      "feedback": {
        "correct": "Right — reverse the power rule: $x^n \\to \\frac{x^{n+1}}{n+1}$.",
        "incorrect": "Differentiate each candidate; the one landing back on the prompt is its antiderivative.",
        "hint": "$x^2 \\to \\frac{x^3}{3}$ and the constant $1 \\to x$."
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "ftc-practice-2",
      "type": "order_list",
      "conceptTag": "antiderivative",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "body": "Put the steps for evaluating a definite integral with the Fundamental Theorem in order."
        }
      ],
      "interaction": {
        "answer": {
          "type": "order_list",
          "orderLabel": "Evaluating a definite integral with the FTC",
          "items": [
            "Find an antiderivative $F(x)$",
            "Plug both limits into $F$",
            "Subtract: $F(b) - F(a)$"
          ]
        }
      },
      "feedback": {
        "correct": "Exactly — find an antiderivative $F$, plug both limits in, then subtract $F(b) - F(a)$.",
        "incorrect": "You need an antiderivative before you can plug in the limits, and you subtract only after both are in.",
        "hint": "Antiderivative first, then plug in both limits, then subtract: $F(b) - F(a)$."
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "ftc-practice-3",
      "type": "drag_drop",
      "conceptTag": "antiderivative",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "body": "Drag the antiderivative of $2x$ into the blank. (For an indefinite integral we would also add $+ C$.)"
        }
      ],
      "interaction": {
        "answer": {
          "type": "drag_drop",
          "prefix": "\\int 2x\\,dx =",
          "blanks": [
            {
              "accept": "x^2"
            }
          ],
          "bank": [
            "x^2",
            "2x^2",
            "\\frac{x^2}{2}",
            "\\frac{x^3}{3}"
          ]
        }
      },
      "feedback": {
        "correct": "Right — $\\frac{d}{dx}(x^2) = 2x$, so $\\int 2x\\,dx = x^2 + C$.",
        "incorrect": "Which tile differentiates back to $2x$?",
        "hint": "Reverse the power rule: $2x \\to x^2$."
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "ftc-practice-4",
      "type": "match",
      "conceptTag": "ftc",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "body": "Match each definite integral to its value, evaluating $F(b) - F(a)$ for each."
        }
      ],
      "interaction": {
        "answer": {
          "type": "match",
          "pairs": [
            {
              "prompt": "$\\int_0^2 2x\\,dx$",
              "match": "4"
            },
            {
              "prompt": "$\\int_0^3 2x\\,dx$",
              "match": "9"
            },
            {
              "prompt": "$\\int_1^3 2x\\,dx$",
              "match": "8"
            },
            {
              "prompt": "$\\int_0^1 3x^2\\,dx$",
              "match": "1"
            }
          ],
          "distractors": [
            "6"
          ]
        }
      },
      "feedback": {
        "correct": "Nice — using $\\int 2x\\,dx = x^2$ and $\\int 3x^2\\,dx = x^3$, every value checks out.",
        "incorrect": "Find the antiderivative, then subtract its values at the two limits.",
        "hint": "$\\int_0^2 2x\\,dx = [x^2]_0^2 = 4$."
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "ftc-practice-5",
      "type": "drag_drop",
      "conceptTag": "ftc",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "body": "The first part of the Fundamental Theorem says differentiating an accumulation function hands back the integrand. Drag the result into the blank."
        }
      ],
      "interaction": {
        "answer": {
          "type": "drag_drop",
          "prefix": "\\frac{d}{dx}\\int_a^x t^2\\,dt =",
          "blanks": [
            {
              "accept": "x^2"
            }
          ],
          "bank": [
            "x^2",
            "\\frac{x^3}{3}",
            "2x",
            "t^2"
          ]
        }
      },
      "feedback": {
        "correct": "Exactly — $\\frac{d}{dx}\\int_a^x t^2\\,dt = x^2$. Differentiation undoes the integral.",
        "incorrect": "The derivative of $\\int_a^x f(t)\\,dt$ is just $f$ evaluated at $x$.",
        "hint": "Replace $t$ with $x$ in the integrand $t^2$."
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "ftc-practice-6",
      "type": "order_list",
      "conceptTag": "ftc",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "body": "Evaluate each integral, then drag them into order from the smallest value to the largest."
        }
      ],
      "interaction": {
        "answer": {
          "type": "order_list",
          "orderLabel": "Smallest → largest value",
          "items": [
            "$\\int_0^2 (x-2)\\,dx$",
            "$\\int_1^2 x\\,dx$",
            "$\\int_0^3 2\\,dx$",
            "$\\int_1^3 2x\\,dx$"
          ]
        }
      },
      "feedback": {
        "correct": "Right — the values are $-2$, $1.5$, $6$, and $8$. The first dips below the axis, so its signed area is negative.",
        "incorrect": "Evaluate each integral first — watch the one that dips below the axis — then compare the numbers.",
        "hint": "$\\int_0^2 (x-2)\\,dx = -2$ is smallest (area below the axis); $\\int_1^3 2x\\,dx = 8$ is largest."
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "ftc-practice-7",
      "type": "match",
      "conceptTag": "antiderivative",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "body": "Match each function to its antiderivative."
        }
      ],
      "interaction": {
        "answer": {
          "type": "match",
          "pairs": [
            {
              "prompt": "$2x$",
              "match": "x^2"
            },
            {
              "prompt": "$3x^2$",
              "match": "x^3"
            },
            {
              "prompt": "$4x^3$",
              "match": "x^4"
            },
            {
              "prompt": "$2$",
              "match": "2x"
            }
          ],
          "distractors": [
            "\\frac{x^2}{2}"
          ]
        }
      },
      "feedback": {
        "correct": "Right — differentiate each answer and it returns the prompt.",
        "incorrect": "Differentiate each option; it should give the prompt back.",
        "hint": "$2x \\to x^2$ and the constant $2 \\to 2x$."
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "ftc-practice-8",
      "type": "slider_graph",
      "conceptTag": "ftc",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "body": "$\\int_0^t (x - 2)\\,dx$ dips negative, then climbs back. Drag $t$ to where this signed area returns to 0."
        }
      ],
      "interaction": {
        "graph": {
          "fn": "x - 2",
          "domain": [0, 4],
          "yDomain": [-3, 3],
          "sliderLabel": "t",
          "xLabel": "x",
          "yLabel": "f",
          "showSecant": false,
          "showValue": false,
          "showArea": true,
          "areaStart": 0,
          "showAreaValue": false,
          "areaReadoutMath": true,
          "integrand": "(x - 2)",
          "sliderMin": 0,
          "sliderMax": 4,
          "sliderStep": 0.1,
          "initialSlider": 0
        },
        "hintAfterAttempts": 1,
        "answer": { "type": "slider", "value": 4, "tolerance": 0.2 }
      },
      "feedback": {
        "correct": "Yes — $A(t) = \\frac{t^2}{2} - 2t = 0$ at $t = 4$: the negative area on $[0,2]$ exactly cancels the positive area on $[2,4]$.",
        "incorrect": "The signed area is negative while $x < 2$, then grows positive. Find the $t > 0$ where it cancels back to 0.",
        "hint": "$\\frac{t^2}{2} - 2t = 0 \\to \\frac{t}{2}(t - 4) = 0 \\to t = 4$."
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "ftc-practice-9",
      "type": "drag_drop",
      "conceptTag": "antiderivative",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "body": "Drag the antiderivative of $x$ into the blank. (With no limits we would also write $+ C$.)"
        }
      ],
      "interaction": {
        "answer": {
          "type": "drag_drop",
          "prefix": "\\int x\\,dx =",
          "blanks": [
            {
              "accept": "\\frac{x^2}{2}"
            }
          ],
          "bank": [
            "\\frac{x^2}{2}",
            "x^2",
            "\\frac{x^3}{3}",
            "2x"
          ]
        }
      },
      "feedback": {
        "correct": "Right — $\\frac{d}{dx}\\!\\left(\\frac{x^2}{2}\\right) = x$, so $\\int x\\,dx = \\frac{x^2}{2} + C$.",
        "incorrect": "Which tile differentiates back to $x$?",
        "hint": "Reverse the power rule: $x \\to \\frac{x^2}{2}$."
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "ftc-practice-10",
      "type": "drag_drop",
      "conceptTag": "ftc",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "body": "Evaluate $\\int_1^3 2x\\,dx$ with $F(x) = x^2$ by filling in $F(3) - F(1)$."
        }
      ],
      "interaction": {
        "answer": {
          "type": "drag_drop",
          "prefix": "\\int_1^3 2x\\,dx = F(3) - F(1) =",
          "blanks": [
            {
              "accept": "9"
            },
            {
              "accept": "1",
              "connector": "-"
            }
          ],
          "bank": [
            "9",
            "1",
            "8",
            "6"
          ]
        }
      },
      "feedback": {
        "correct": "Exactly — $F(3) - F(1) = 9 - 1 = 8$, so $\\int_1^3 2x\\,dx = 8$.",
        "incorrect": "With $F(x) = x^2$, compute $F(3)$ and $F(1)$, then subtract in that order.",
        "hint": "$F(3) = 3^2 = 9$ and $F(1) = 1^2 = 1$, so $9 - 1 = 8$."
      }
    }
  ]
}
